{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LNnskNt61Vwhfg7zpSQ4u1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Criterions Software Inc — Product Research\n     2→\n     3→Researched: 2026-02-14\n     4→Developer website: https://criterions.com/\n     5→\n     6→## Overview\n     7→\n     8→Criterions Software Inc is a small, privately held healthcare IT company headquartered in Garden City, NY (some sources cite Great Neck, NY). The company has been in business for over 30 years and has approximately 7–12 employees depending on the source. They develop an integrated cloud-based EHR and practice management suite marketed to independent medical practices, multi-provider clinics, and medical billing services of all sizes. Their target market is ambulatory practices across a very wide range of specialties — their website lists nearly 50 supported specialties, from family medicine and internal medicine to surgical subspecialties, behavioral health, dentistry, ophthalmology, and more.\n     9→\n    10→Criterions is a small niche vendor without a large public market presence. They do not appear to have significant venture funding or private equity backing. The company appears to be a modest, long-standing player in the ambulatory EHR/PM space, focused on direct relationships with independent practices and billing companies.\n    11→\n    12→## Product: Criterions EHR (part of Criterions Medical Suite / TCMS)\n    13→\n    14→CHPL ID: 10171\n    15→\n    16→### What It Is\n    17→\n    18→Criterions EHR is a cloud-based, ONC-certified electronic health records system that is part of a broader integrated suite called \"The Criterions Medical Suite\" (TCMS). The certified product is listed as \"Criterions EHR 4.0 Complete EHR Ambulatory.\" It is broadly certified across clinical documentation (a)(1)–(a)(5), (a)(12), (a)(14)–(a)(15), transitions of care (b)(1)–(b)(3), patient portal (e)(1), clinical quality measures (c)(1)–(c)(3), public health reporting (f)(1), (f)(5), and FHIR API access (g)(10). The certification is for \"All Ambulatory Practices.\"\n    19→\n    20→The certified EHR module is part of a larger integrated product suite that includes practice management/billing, patient portal, e-prescribing, scheduling, lab interfaces, and document management. These are marketed as an integrated platform rather than standalone products.\n    21→\n    22→### Users & Market\n    23→\n    24→The product is designed for independent and growing medical practices, from single-provider offices to multi-location clinics, as well as medical billing services. Criterions supports an unusually wide range of specialties — nearly 50 are listed on their website including allergy, anesthesiology, bariatric surgery, behavioral health, cardiology, chiropractic, dentistry, dermatology, emergency medicine, endocrinology, ENT, family medicine, gastroenterology, general surgery, geriatrics, hematology/oncology, hospitalist, infectious disease, internal medicine, long-term care, mental health, multi-specialty, nephrology, neurology, neurosurgery, OB-GYN, occupational medicine, oncology, ophthalmology, optometry, orthopedics, pain management, pathology, pediatrics, physical therapy, plastic surgery, podiatry, psychiatry, psychology, pulmonology, radiology, rheumatology, sleep medicine, surgery, SurgiCenter, urgent care, urology, and vascular surgery.\n    25→\n    26→Given the company's small size (7–12 employees), the customer base is likely modest. No specific customer counts or notable deployments were found in public materials. The login portal at portal.nymed.com suggests at least some New York-area medical practices as customers. Third-party reviews on Capterra indicate a small number of reviews with generally positive sentiment, noting the vendor's responsiveness and willingness to customize.\n    27→\n    28→### Modules & Functionality\n    29→\n    30→Based on the vendor's website and feature pages, the Criterions Medical Suite includes the following integrated modules:\n    31→\n    32→**Electronic Health Records (EHR)**\n    33→- Customizable charting tools with specialty-specific templates\n    34→- Patient vitals tracking\n    35→- Clinical documentation for encounters\n    36→- Problem lists, medication lists, allergy lists (implied by (a)(1)–(a)(5) certification)\n    37→- Clinical decision support (certified for (a)(2), (a)(4))\n    38→- Implantable device tracking (certified for (a)(14))\n    39→- Social, psychological, and behavioral data (certified for (a)(15))\n    40→\n    41→**E-Prescribing**\n    42→- Integrated e-prescribing including controlled substances (EPCS)\n    43→- Prescription history access\n    44→- Drug interaction monitoring\n    45→- Controlled substance tracking\n    46→- Prescription fulfillment and refill request tracking\n    47→- Integrated with Surescripts network (SureScripts certificate displayed on disclosures page)\n    48→- NewCrop integration mentioned in the mandatory disclosures page\n    49→\n    50→**Practice Management / Billing**\n    51→- Insurance verification and eligibility checking\n    52→- Electronic superbill generation and transmission\n    53→- Claims submission and clean claim processing\n    54→- Denial tracking\n    55→- Accounts receivable (A/R) management\n    56→- Payment posting (automated and manual)\n    57→- Patient payment plans and online payment processing\n    58→- Daily transaction reports, multi-practice reports, PQRS reports\n    59→- Revenue cycle management\n    60→- Claredi 5010 certified (for electronic claims)\n    61→\n    62→**Scheduling**\n    63→- Drag-and-drop appointment calendars\n    64→- Recurring appointment tools\n    65→- Task queues\n    66→- Automated appointment reminders (email and text)\n    67→- Real-time analytics on scheduling\n    68→\n    69→**Patient Portal**\n    70→- 24/7 patient access to health information\n    71→- Online appointment scheduling and check-in\n    72→- Electronic patient intake forms (demographics, insurance, medical history, social history, family history, medications, allergies, pharmacy preferences, consent forms, medical questionnaires)\n    73→- Prescription refill requests\n    74→- Secure HIPAA-compliant messaging between patients and practice\n    75→- Message routing to appropriate staff based on message type\n    76→- Online bill viewing and payment (credit card)\n    77→- Document and ID upload\n    78→\n    79→**Lab Interfaces**\n    80→- Electronic lab ordering\n    81→- Automatic receipt and filing of lab results\n    82→- Results filed to ordering provider's queue\n    83→- LOINC-coded results with automatic MIPS measure calculation\n    84→- Connections to labs, imaging groups, and public health organizations (specific partners not listed publicly)\n    85→\n    86→**Document Management**\n    87→- Folder creation and organization\n    88→- Document annotations\n    89→- Digital signature locking\n    90→- Patient documentation storage\n    91→\n    92→**Reporting & Analytics**\n    93→- Financial reports and analytics\n    94→- Practice performance dashboards\n    95→- Patient outcome reporting\n    96→- Clinical quality measures (CQM) support (certified for (c)(1)–(c)(3))\n    97→- MIPS/quality reporting\n    98→\n    99→**Transitions of Care**\n   100→- C-CDA generation and transmission (certified for (b)(1)–(b)(3))\n   101→- Integration with EMRDirect (mentioned on mandatory disclosures page) for Direct messaging\n   102→\n   103→**Public Health Reporting**\n   104→- Immunization registry reporting (certified for (f)(1))\n   105→- Cancer case reporting (certified for (f)(5))\n   106→\n   107→**Administrative Features**\n   108→- Role-based access controls\n   109→- Audit logging of record access and modifications\n   110→- Recall procedures for follow-up visit reminders\n   111→- User access controls limiting record visibility\n   112→- Referral management\n   113→\n   114→### Data & Content\n   115→\n   116→Based on the features described above, the Criterions Medical Suite stores and manages the following categories of data:\n   117→\n   118→**Clinical Data**: Patient demographics, encounter notes/clinical documentation, vital signs, problem lists, medication lists, allergy lists, immunization records, lab orders and results (LOINC-coded), social history, family history, past medical history, implantable device records, clinical decision support alerts/interactions, referral information, and C-CDA documents.\n   119→\n   120→**Prescription Data**: Active and historical prescriptions, controlled substance prescriptions, drug interaction alerts, prescription fulfillment tracking, refill requests, and pharmacy information — all flowing through the Surescripts/NewCrop integration.\n   121→\n   122→**Billing/Financial Data**: Insurance information (plans, eligibility verification results), superbills, claims, denial records, accounts receivable, payment history, patient payment plans, patient ledger entries, transaction records, and financial reports.\n   123→\n   124→**Scheduling Data**: Appointment calendars, appointment history, recurring appointment patterns, reminder records, and no-show tracking.\n   125→\n   126→**Patient Portal Data**: Patient-submitted intake forms (demographics, insurance, medical questionnaires, consent forms), secure messages between patients and practice staff, online payment records, uploaded documents and IDs.\n   127→\n   128→**Administrative Data**: User accounts and roles, audit logs (who accessed/modified what records), document management records (with annotations and digital signatures), recall/follow-up reminders.\n   129→\n   130→**Reporting Data**: Clinical quality measure calculations, MIPS measure data, practice performance analytics, financial analytics.\n   131→\n   132→**Public Health Data**: Immunization registry submissions, cancer case reports.\n   133→\n   134→The vendor website does not specifically mention imaging/PACS storage, fax management, or integrated telehealth — though these may exist as features not prominently marketed. The website also doesn't detail how historical data is retained or archived.\n   135→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. The company has been in business for over 30 years and has approximately 7–12 employees depending on the source. They develop an integrated cloud-based EHR and practice management suite marketed to independent medical practices, multi-provider clinics, and medical billing services of all sizes. Their target market is ambulatory practices across a very wide range of specialties — their website lists nearly 50 supported specialties, from family medicine and internal medicine to surgical subspecialties, behavioral health, dentistry, ophthalmology, and more.\n\nCriterions is a small niche vendor without a large public market presence. They do not appear to have significant venture funding or private equity backing. The company appears to be a modest, long-standing player in the ambulatory EHR/PM space, focused on direct relationships with independent practices and billing companies.\n\n## Product: Criterions EHR (part of Criterions Medical Suite / TCMS)\n\nCHPL ID: 10171\n\n### What It Is\n\nCriterions EHR is a cloud-based, ONC-certified electronic health records system that is part of a broader integrated suite called \"The Criterions Medical Suite\" (TCMS). The certified product is listed as \"Criterions EHR 4.0 Complete EHR Ambulatory.\" It is broadly certified across clinical documentation (a)(1)–(a)(5), (a)(12), (a)(14)–(a)(15), transitions of care (b)(1)–(b)(3), patient portal (e)(1), clinical quality measures (c)(1)–(c)(3), public health reporting (f)(1), (f)(5), and FHIR API access (g)(10). The certification is for \"All Ambulatory Practices.\"\n\nThe certified EHR module is part of a larger integrated product suite that includes practice management/billing, patient portal, e-prescribing, scheduling, lab interfaces, and document management. These are marketed as an integrated platform rather than standalone products.\n\n### Users & Market\n\nThe product is designed for independent and growing medical practices, from single-provider offices to multi-location clinics, as well as medical billing services. Criterions supports an unusually wide range of specialties — nearly 50 are listed on their website including allergy, anesthesiology, bariatric surgery, behavioral health, cardiology, chiropractic, dentistry, dermatology, emergency medicine, endocrinology, ENT, family medicine, gastroenterology, general surgery, geriatrics, hematology/oncology, hospitalist, infectious disease, internal medicine, long-term care, mental health, multi-specialty, nephrology, neurology, neurosurgery, OB-GYN, occupational medicine, oncology, ophthalmology, optometry, orthopedics, pain management, pathology, pediatrics, physical therapy, plastic surgery, podiatry, psychiatry, psychology, pulmonology, radiology, rheumatology, sleep medicine, surgery, SurgiCenter, urgent care, urology, and vascular surgery.\n\nGiven the company's small size (7–12 employees), the customer base is likely modest. No specific customer counts or notable deployments were found in public materials. The login portal at portal.nymed.com suggests at least some New York-area medical practices as customers. Third-party reviews on Capterra indicate a small number of reviews with generally positive sentiment, noting the vendor's responsiveness and willingness to customize.\n\n### Modules & Functionality\n\nBased on the vendor's website and feature pages, the Criterions Medical Suite includes the following integrated modules:\n\n**Electronic Health Records (EHR)**\n- Customizable charting tools with specialty-specific templates\n- Patient vitals tracking\n- Clinical documentation for encounters\n- Problem lists, medication lists, allergy lists (implied by (a)(1)–(a)(5) certification)\n- Clinical decision support (certified for (a)(2), (a)(4))\n- Implantable device tracking (certified for (a)(14))\n- Social, psychological, and behavioral data (certified for (a)(15))\n\n**E-Prescribing**\n- Integrated e-prescribing including controlled substances (EPCS)\n- Prescription history access\n- Drug interaction monitoring\n- Controlled substance tracking\n- Prescription fulfillment and refill request tracking\n- Integrated with Surescripts network (SureScripts certificate displayed on disclosures page)\n- NewCrop integration mentioned in the mandatory disclosures page\n\n**Practice Management / Billing**\n- Insurance verification and eligibility checking\n- Electronic superbill generation and transmission\n- Claims submission and clean claim processing\n- Denial tracking\n- Accounts receivable (A/R) management\n- Payment posting (automated and manual)\n- Patient payment plans and online payment processing\n- Daily transaction reports, multi-practice reports, PQRS reports\n- Revenue cycle management\n- Claredi 5010 certified (for electronic claims)\n\n**Scheduling**\n- Drag-and-drop appointment calendars\n- Recurring appointment tools\n- Task queues\n- Automated appointment reminders (email and text)\n- Real-time analytics on scheduling\n\n**Patient Portal**\n- 24/7 patient access to health information\n- Online appointment scheduling and check-in\n- Electronic patient intake forms (demographics, insurance, medical history, social history, family history, medications, allergies, pharmacy preferences, consent forms, medical questionnaires)\n- Prescription refill requests\n- Secure HIPAA-compliant messaging between patients and practice\n- Message routing to appropriate staff based on message type\n- Online bill viewing and payment (credit card)\n- Document and ID upload\n\n**Lab Interfaces**\n- Electronic lab ordering\n- Automatic receipt and filing of lab results\n- Results filed to ordering provider's queue\n- LOINC-coded results with automatic MIPS measure calculation\n- Connections to labs, imaging groups, and public health organizations (specific partners not listed publicly)\n\n**Document Management**\n- Folder creation and organization\n- Document annotations\n- Digital signature locking\n- Patient documentation storage\n\n**Reporting & Analytics**\n- Financial reports and analytics\n- Practice performance dashboards\n- Patient outcome reporting\n- Clinical quality measures (CQM) support (certified for (c)(1)–(c)(3))\n- MIPS/quality reporting\n\n**Transitions of Care**\n- C-CDA generation and transmission (certified for (b)(1)–(b)(3))\n- Integration with EMRDirect (mentioned on mandatory disclosures page) for Direct messaging\n\n**Public Health Reporting**\n- Immunization registry reporting (certified for (f)(1))\n- Cancer case reporting (certified for (f)(5))\n\n**Administrative Features**\n- Role-based access controls\n- Audit logging of record access and modifications\n- Recall procedures for follow-up visit reminders\n- User access controls limiting record visibility\n- Referral management\n\n### Data & Content\n\nBased on the features described above, the Criterions Medical Suite stores and manages the following categories of data:\n\n**Clinical Data**: Patient demographics, encounter notes/clinical documentation, vital signs, problem lists, medication lists, allergy lists, immunization records, lab orders and results (LOINC-coded), social history, family history, past medical history, implantable device records, clinical decision support alerts/interactions, referral information, and C-CDA documents.\n\n**Prescription Data**: Active and historical prescriptions, controlled substance prescriptions, drug interaction alerts, prescription fulfillment tracking, refill requests, and pharmacy information — all flowing through the Surescripts/NewCrop integration.\n\n**Billing/Financial Data**: Insurance information (plans, eligibility verification results), superbills, claims, denial records, accounts receivable, payment history, patient payment plans, patient ledger entries, transaction records, and financial reports.\n\n**Scheduling Data**: Appointment calendars, appointment history, recurring appointment patterns, reminder records, and no-show tracking.\n\n**Patient Portal Data**: Patient-submitted intake forms (demographics, insurance, medical questionnaires, consent forms), secure messages between patients and practice staff, online payment records, uploaded documents and IDs.\n\n**Administrative Data**: User accounts and roles, audit logs (who accessed/modified what records), document management records (with annotations and digital signatures), recall/follow-up reminders.\n\n**Reporting Data**: Clinical quality measure calculations, MIPS measure data, practice performance analytics, financial analytics.\n\n**Public Health Data**: Immunization registry submissions, cancer case reports.\n\nThe vendor website does not specifically mention imaging/PACS storage, fax management, or integrated telehealth — though these may exist as features not prominently marketed. The website also doesn't detail how historical data is retained or archived.\n","numLines":135,"startLine":1,"totalLines":135}}}

Your emailed or printed chart will include your chart information\nthat was stored by the practice.\n\nHow to read your CCDA:\n\nA CCDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture) file is an XML-based standard\nfor the electronic exchange of structured clinical healthcare information. It's used to\nshare patient summary information, including problems, medications, allergies, and\nprocedures, among healthcare providers. CCDA files are often used for interoperability\nbetween different electronic health record (EHR) systems. You can use this file to send\ninformation to another doctor you'd like to see. {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TsZh25LkDKpUe6dSKovLMS","type":"tool_result","content":"2022 CURES DISCLOSURES\n\nMulti-Factor Authentication\nProtecting Patient health information is of critical importance to practices. To ensure that each practice’s\ninformation is as secure as possible the Criterions EHR 4 offers Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) through\nSMS and/or email based on a practice’s configuration. When activated, MFA requires the entry of a unique\none-time password (OTP) sent via SMS/email to validate the unique user after entry of username and\npassword. Any user who cannot supply the MFA OTP code will be denied entry to the system in its\nentirety. Upon login, the Criterions EHR requires additional MFA compliance for the transmission of\nElectronically Prescribed Controlled Substances (EPCS). This additional layer of security ensures that\ncontrolled medications are not transmitted without MFA of the submitting physician. Criterions Portal\napplications support MFA through SMS and/or email OTP.\n\nEHI\nThe Criterions EHR allows customers to export industry-standard patient information in XML format using\nCCDA architecture and our Email/Print Chart functionality. Exports can be performed without intervention\nfrom programming or Criterions Software, Inc and without charge for individual patients, groups of\npatients, or automated scheduled export. Regular updates are performed in compliance with standards as\nfound at https://www.hl7.org/implement/standards/ .\n\n516.466.1942 | info@criterions.com | www.criterions.com","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a2b78740-7fd9-4075-bb1d-e7fa85220279","uuid":"6e97a19c-24ab-4239-88eb-b790b3379645","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"2022 CURES DISCLOSURES\n\nMulti-Factor Authentication\nProtecting Patient health information is of critical importance to practices. To ensure that each practice’s\ninformation is as secure as possible the Criterions EHR 4 offers Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) through\nSMS and/or email based on a practice’s configuration. When activated, MFA requires the entry of a unique\none-time password (OTP) sent via SMS/email to validate the unique user after entry of username and\npassword. Any user who cannot supply the MFA OTP code will be denied entry to the system in its\nentirety. Upon login, the Criterions EHR requires additional MFA compliance for the transmission of\nElectronically Prescribed Controlled Substances (EPCS). This additional layer of security ensures that\ncontrolled medications are not transmitted without MFA of the submitting physician. Criterions Portal\napplications support MFA through SMS and/or email OTP.\n\nEHI\nThe Criterions EHR allows customers to export industry-standard patient information in XML format using\nCCDA architecture and our Email/Print Chart functionality. Exports can be performed without intervention\nfrom programming or Criterions Software, Inc and without charge for individual patients, groups of\npatients, or automated scheduled export. Regular updates are performed in compliance with standards as\nfound at https://www.hl7.org/implement/standards/ .\n\n516.466.1942 | info@criterions.com | www.criterions.com","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false}}

subscription.\nThere is integration with PM system and PM\nsystem is the source for capturing demographic data as part of patient intake process\n\nThis capability requires the Criterions EHR product which may be sold to customers with\neither a one-time License fee plus an annual, quarterly or monthly fee per provider or user,\nor as an annual, quarterly or monthly SaaS subscription fees based on the number of\nproviders and users with some one-time set-up fees.\nTraining and implementation fees as well as travel expenses are billed separately.\n\n170.315(a)(6) Problem List\n\nThis functionality enables a user to electronically record, change, and access a patient’s active problem list over multiple encounters, following ICD-9, ICD10, and SNOMED standards.\n\nThis capability requires the Criterions EHR product which may be sold to customers with\neither a one-time License fee plus an annual, quarterly or monthly fee per provider or user,\nor as an annual, quarterly or monthly SaaS subscription fees based on the number of\nproviders and users with some one-time set-up fees.\nTraining and implementation fees as well as travel expenses are billed separately.\n\n170.315(a)(7) Medication List\n\nThis functionality enables a user to electronically record, change, and access a patient’s active medication list as well as medication history over multiple encounters, following\nRxNorm, CVX, and NDC standards.\n\nThis capability requires the Criterions EHR product which may be sold to customers with\neither a one-time License fee plus an annual, quarterly or monthly fee per provider or user,\nor as an annual, quarterly or monthly SaaS subscription fees based on the number of\nproviders and users with some one-time set-up fees.\nTraining and implementation fees as well as travel expenses are billed separately.\n\n170.315(a)(8) Medication Allergy List\n\nThis functionality enables a user to electronically record, The solution uses RxNorm\nand NCPD standards, and the SureScripts infrastructure for prescription transmission to the\npharmacy.\n\nThis capability requires the Criterions EHR product which may be sold to customers with\neither a one-time License fee plus an annual, quarterly or monthly fee per provider or user,\nor as an annual, quarterly or monthly SaaS subscription fees based on the number of\nproviders and users with some one-time set-up fees.\nTraining and implementation fees as well as travel expenses are billed separately.\nThis capability also requires a separate ePrescribing annual or monthly fee.\nControlled substances require additional services from Newcrop which may have additional\nregistration and contract required.\n\n170.315(b)(6) Data export\n\nThis functionality enables a user to electronically create a set of export summaries for all\npatients in C-CDA format that represents the\nmost current clinical information about each\npatient. Secure\nmessages may be initiated by the provider using the EHR or the patient using the patient\nportal, and may include clinical data, administrative data, and other information.\nThis requires an integration interface with the\nEHR and allows for the secure message to be\nexchanged with the provider in their own EHR\nworkflows.\n\n170.315(e)(3) Patient Health Information Capture\n\nPublic Health\n\nThis functionality enables user to capture patient health information into chart to support\nbetter patient engagement in their care. {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CanCbCH1s7X5H4ZeqSbUGa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017aFLTFmTuWAeavhzBSWoom","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/jmandel/hobby/ehi-export-analysis/results/criterions-software-inc/ehi-export-report.md","content":"# Criterions Software Inc — EHI Export Documentation\n\nCollected: 2026-02-14\n\n## Source\n- Registered URL: https://criterions.com/cures-disclosures-2022/\n- CHPL IDs: 10171\n- Product: Criterions EHR v4.0\n- Developer: Criterions Software Inc\n\n## Navigation Journal\n\nThe registered URL returns HTTP 200 directly. It is a WordPress page (Divi theme) hosted behind Cloudflare on WP Engine.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sI -L \"https://criterions.com/cures-disclosures-2022/\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n# HTTP/2 200, content-type: text/html; charset=UTF-8\n```\n\nThe page is titled \"Certifications & Documentation\" and contains exactly three button-links:\n\n1. **\"2022 CURES Disclosure\"** → `https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/2022-CURES-DISCLOSURES.pdf`\n2. **\"Patient EHI Data Export\"** → `https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/Patient-EHI-Data-Export-Overview.pdf`\n3. **\"Mandatory Disclosure 2022\"** → `https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/MandatoryDisclosure2022.pdf`\n\nAll three are direct PDF downloads. No accordions, no JavaScript rendering needed — the buttons are plain `<a>` tags with `target=\"_blank\"`.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/Patient-EHI-Data-Export-Overview.pdf\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o Patient-EHI-Data-Export-Overview.pdf\ncurl -sL \"https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/2022-CURES-DISCLOSURES.pdf\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o 2022-CURES-DISCLOSURES.pdf\ncurl -sL \"https://criterions.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/MandatoryDisclosure2022.pdf\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o MandatoryDisclosure2022.pdf\n```\n\nAll three files verified as actual PDF documents.\n\n## What Was Found\n\n### Patient EHI Data Export Overview (1 page)\n\nThis is the primary EHI export documentation. It is a single-page PDF titled \"Patient EHI Data Export Overview and Instructions.\" The document states:\n\n> \"Your Patient Electronic Health Information (EHI) files are all sent via 'Email/Print of your Chart' along with the option to Download the CCDA file through our Criterions Electronic Health Records System. Your emailed or printed chart will include your chart information that was stored by the practice.\"\n\nThe document then explains what a CCDA file is and lists 22 clinical data categories included in the CCDA export:\n\n1. Allergies\n2. Assessment\n3. Consult Note\n4. Diagnostic Imaging Study\n5. Encounters\n6. Functional Status\n7. Goals\n8. Health Concern\n9. History and Physical\n10. Immunizations\n11. Laboratory Report Narrative\n12. Medical Equipment\n13. Medications\n14. Mental Status\n15. Plan of Care\n16. Problem List\n17. Procedures\n18. Progress Note\n19. Reason for Referral\n20. Results\n21. Social History\n22. Vital Signs\n\nThe export mechanism is described as \"Email/Print of your Chart\" plus a CCDA download option. The document is patient-facing — it instructs patients on how to read CCDA files rather than providing technical details about the export format.\n\n### 2022 CURES Disclosures (1 page)\n\nThis single-page document has two sections:\n\n1. **Multi-Factor Authentication** — describes MFA implementation\n2. **EHI** — states: \"The Criterions EHR allows customers to export industry-standard patient information in XML format using CCDA architecture and our Email/Print Chart functionality. Exports can be performed without intervention from programming or Criterions Software, Inc and without charge for individual patients, groups of patients, or automated scheduled export.\"\n\n### Mandatory Disclosure 2022 (9 pages)\n\nA comprehensive mandatory disclosure table listing all certified capabilities, descriptions, and costs. The relevant entry is:\n\n- **§170.315(b)(10) Electronic Health Information export**: appears as a row header on page 5, but the description column for this row is blank — the page layout collapses it into the surrounding (b)(6) Data export section, which says: \"Allow a practice to create individual and group exports of PHI without programming intervention.\"\n- **170.315(b)(6) Data export**: \"This functionality enables a user to electronically create a set of export summaries for all patients in C-CDA format that represents the most current clinical information about each patient. It includes clinical data defined in the Common Clinical Data Set, the reason for referral, and the referring or transitioning provider's name and office contact information.\"\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\n\nThe export documentation describes a **C-CDA-based clinical summary export** that covers 22 clinical data categories. Comparing this against what Criterions EHR actually stores (per the product research):\n\n**Clearly covered (clinical data):**\n- Allergies, medications, problem lists, immunizations, vital signs — core clinical data\n- Encounters, procedures, results/labs — encounter-level data\n- Social history, functional status, mental status — social/behavioral data\n- Medical equipment (implantable devices)\n- Goals, plan of care, assessments\n- Progress notes, H&P, consult notes — clinical documentation\n\n**Clearly missing:**\n- **Billing/financial data** — insurance, claims, superbills, A/R, payment history, denial tracking, patient payment plans. The product has a full practice management/billing module. None of this appears in the export.\n- **Scheduling data** — appointment calendars, appointment history, recurring appointments, reminders. No mention.\n- **Patient portal data** — intake forms, secure messages, uploaded documents/IDs, online payment records. No mention.\n- **Prescription management data** — e-prescribing transaction history, controlled substance tracking, refill requests, pharmacy information. While \"Medications\" is listed, the Surescripts/NewCrop integration data (fulfillment tracking, dispensing records, EPCS audit trails) is absent.\n- **Administrative data** — user accounts, audit logs, role-based access records. While the system has audit logging (certified for (d)(2)), audit data is not in the export.\n- **Document management** — folders, annotations, digital signatures. No mention.\n- **Reporting data** — CQM calculations, MIPS data, practice analytics. No mention.\n- **Public health submissions** — immunization registry submissions, cancer case reports. No mention.\n- **Referral management records** — while \"Reason for Referral\" is in the CCDA, the referral management workflow data is likely not captured.\n\n### Export Format & Standards\n\nThe export is **C-CDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture)** — an XML-based standard. This is a well-recognized clinical document standard, but it is fundamentally a **clinical summary format**, not a comprehensive data export format.\n\nC-CDA was designed for transitions of care and patient summaries. It has well-defined sections for clinical data but no native support for:\n- Billing/claims data\n- Scheduling data\n- Administrative/audit data\n- Practice management data\n- Portal interaction data\n\nThis is a classic case of **using the (g)(10)/(b)(1) clinical summary as the (b)(10) export**. The C-CDA export covers the \"Common Clinical Data Set\" (now USCDI) but not \"all electronic health information\" as required by 170.315(b)(10). The product stores extensive billing, scheduling, administrative, and portal data that cannot be represented in C-CDA format.\n\nThe 2022 CURES Disclosures document even says the export uses \"industry-standard patient information in XML format using CCDA architecture\" — acknowledging it's a standards-based clinical summary, not a comprehensive data dump.\n\n### Documentation Quality\n\nThe documentation is **minimal**:\n\n- The EHI export overview is a single page, patient-facing, explaining what a CCDA is\n- There is no data dictionary — no table/field definitions, no schema documentation\n- There are no worked examples or sample export files\n- There is no technical documentation describing the CCDA's specific mapping, extensions, or constraints\n- There is no description of how the \"Email/Print Chart\" functionality works technically\n- A developer could not implement an import based on this documentation alone — they would need to rely entirely on the C-CDA standard specification and hope Criterions follows it faithfully\n\nThe documentation reads as a compliance checkbox rather than a genuine effort to document the export mechanism. It appears designed for patients (\"How to read your CCDA\") rather than for technical interoperability.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n\n- **Granularity**: The documentation lists 22 section names but provides no field-level detail, data types, value sets, or constraints\n- **Relationships**: No documentation of entity relationships\n- **Coded fields**: No documentation of code systems used beyond mentioning ICD-9/10, SNOMED, RxNorm in the mandatory disclosure\n- **Versioning**: The EHI export PDF was uploaded May 2024; the CURES disclosures are from August 2022. The mandatory disclosure is from December 2022. No version history or changelog.\n- **Sample data**: None provided\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nCriterions has produced the minimum viable documentation for (b)(10) compliance: a statement that patients can export their chart as a CCDA, plus a list of what sections the CCDA contains. This approach has several fundamental problems:\n\n1. **It's not actually a (b)(10) export** — it's a C-CDA clinical summary that covers roughly the same data as the (g)(10) FHIR API and (b)(1) transitions of care. The extensive billing, scheduling, administrative, and portal data stored by the product is entirely absent.\n\n2. **The documentation provides no technical detail** — there's no data dictionary, no schema, no mapping documentation. The one-page patient-facing overview is the entirety of the technical documentation.\n\n3. **The export mechanism is described vaguely** — \"Email/Print of your Chart\" plus CCDA download. There's no documentation of batch export capabilities, automation, or how the \"automated scheduled export\" mentioned in the CURES disclosure actually works.\n\nThis is consistent with a small vendor (7-12 employees) that has treated (b)(10) as a repackaging of their existing C-CDA/transitions of care capability rather than building a genuine comprehensive data export.\n\n## Access Summary\n- Final URL (after redirects): https://criterions.com/cures-disclosures-2022/\n- Status: found\n- Required browser: no\n- Navigation complexity: direct_link (three buttons on a single page)\n- Anti-bot issues: none (Cloudflare present but no blocking)\n\n## Obstacles & Dead Ends\n\nNone. The page loaded cleanly, all three PDF links worked, and the files downloaded without issues. The simplicity of the page (three buttons, three PDFs) made collection straightforward. The challenge is not access — it's that there simply isn't much documentation to collect.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":266,"cache_read_input_tokens":77004,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":266},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a2b78740-7fd9-4075-bb1d-e7fa85220279","uuid":"4300f38a-a788-4c9e-991e-2bf7cd056b70"}

Exports can be performed without intervention from programming or Criterions Software, Inc and without charge for individual patients, groups of patients, or automated scheduled export.\"\n\n### Mandatory Disclosure 2022 (9 pages)\n\nA comprehensive mandatory disclosure table listing all certified capabilities, descriptions, and costs. The relevant entry is:\n\n- **§170.315(b)(10) Electronic Health Information export**: appears as a row header on page 5, but the description column for this row is blank — the page layout collapses it into the surrounding (b)(6) Data export section, which says: \"Allow a practice to create individual and group exports of PHI without programming intervention.\"\n- **170.315(b)(6) Data export**: \"This functionality enables a user to electronically create a set of export summaries for all patients in C-CDA format that represents the most current clinical information about each patient. It includes clinical data defined in the Common Clinical Data Set, the reason for referral, and the referring or transitioning provider's name and office contact information.\"\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\n\nThe export documentation describes a **C-CDA-based clinical summary export** that covers 22 clinical data categories. Comparing this against what Criterions EHR actually stores (per the product research):\n\n**Clearly covered (clinical data):**\n- Allergies, medications, problem lists, immunizations, vital signs — core clinical data\n- Encounters, procedures, results/labs — encounter-level data\n- Social history, functional status, mental status — social/behavioral data\n- Medical equipment (implantable devices)\n- Goals, plan of care, assessments\n- Progress notes, H&P, consult notes — clinical documentation\n\n**Clearly missing:**\n- **Billing/financial data** — insurance, claims, superbills, A/R, payment history, denial tracking, patient payment plans. The product has a full practice management/billing module. None of this appears in the export.\n- **Scheduling data** — appointment calendars, appointment history, recurring appointments, reminders. No mention.\n- **Patient portal data** — intake forms, secure messages, uploaded documents/IDs, online payment records. No mention.\n- **Prescription management data** — e-prescribing transaction history, controlled substance tracking, refill requests, pharmacy information. While \"Medications\" is listed, the Surescripts/NewCrop integration data (fulfillment tracking, dispensing records, EPCS audit trails) is absent.\n- **Administrative data** — user accounts, audit logs, role-based access records. While the system has audit logging (certified for (d)(2)), audit data is not in the export.\n- **Document management** — folders, annotations, digital signatures. No mention.\n- **Reporting data** — CQM calculations, MIPS data, practice analytics. No mention.\n- **Public health submissions** — immunization registry submissions, cancer case reports. No mention.\n- **Referral management records** — while \"Reason for Referral\" is in the CCDA, the referral management workflow data is likely not captured.\n\n### Export Format & Standards\n\nThe export is **C-CDA (Consolidated Clinical Document Architecture)** — an XML-based standard. This is a well-recognized clinical document standard, but it is fundamentally a **clinical summary format**, not a comprehensive data export format.\n\nC-CDA was designed for transitions of care and patient summaries. It has well-defined sections for clinical data but no native support for:\n- Billing/claims data\n- Scheduling data\n- Administrative/audit data\n- Practice management data\n- Portal interaction data\n\nThis is a classic case of **using the (g)(10)/(b)(1) clinical summary as the (b)(10) export**. The C-CDA export covers the \"Common Clinical Data Set\" (now USCDI) but not \"all electronic health information\" as required by 170.315(b)(10). The product stores extensive billing, scheduling, administrative, and portal data that cannot be represented in C-CDA format.\n\nThe 2022 CURES Disclosures document even says the export uses \"industry-standard patient information in XML format using CCDA architecture\" — acknowledging it's a standards-based clinical summary, not a comprehensive data dump.\n\n### Documentation Quality\n\nThe documentation is **minimal**:\n\n- The EHI export overview is a single page, patient-facing, explaining what a CCDA is\n- There is no data dictionary — no table/field definitions, no schema documentation\n- There are no worked examples or sample export files\n- There is no technical documentation describing the CCDA's specific mapping, extensions, or constraints\n- There is no description of how the \"Email/Print Chart\" functionality works technically\n- A developer could not implement an import based on this documentation alone — they would need to rely entirely on the C-CDA standard specification and hope Criterions follows it faithfully\n\nThe documentation reads as a compliance checkbox rather than a genuine effort to document the export mechanism. It appears designed for patients (\"How to read your CCDA\") rather than for technical interoperability.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n\n- **Granularity**: The documentation lists 22 section names but provides no field-level detail, data types, value sets, or constraints\n- **Relationships**: No documentation of entity relationships\n- **Coded fields**: No documentation of code systems used beyond mentioning ICD-9/10, SNOMED, RxNorm in the mandatory disclosure\n- **Versioning**: The EHI export PDF was uploaded May 2024; the CURES disclosures are from August 2022. The mandatory disclosure is from December 2022. No version history or changelog.\n- **Sample data**: None provided\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nCriterions has produced the minimum viable documentation for (b)(10) compliance: a statement that patients can export their chart as a CCDA, plus a list of what sections the CCDA contains. This approach has several fundamental problems:\n\n1. **It's not actually a (b)(10) export** — it's a C-CDA clinical summary that covers roughly the same data as the (g)(10) FHIR API and (b)(1) transitions of care. The extensive billing, scheduling, administrative, and portal data stored by the product is entirely absent.\n\n2. **The documentation provides no technical detail** — there's no data dictionary, no schema, no mapping documentation. The one-page patient-facing overview is the entirety of the technical documentation.\n\n3. **The export mechanism is described vaguely** — \"Email/Print of your Chart\" plus CCDA download. There's no documentation of batch export capabilities, automation, or how the \"automated scheduled export\" mentioned in the CURES disclosure actually works.\n\nThis is consistent with a small vendor (7-12 employees) that has treated (b)(10) as a repackaging of their existing C-CDA/transitions of care capability rather than building a genuine comprehensive data export.\n\n## Access Summary\n- Final URL (after redirects): https://criterions.com/cures-disclosures-2022/\n- Status: found\n- Required browser: no\n- Navigation complexity: direct_link (three buttons on a single page)\n- Anti-bot issues: none (Cloudflare present but no blocking)\n\n## Obstacles & Dead Ends\n\nNone. The page loaded cleanly, all three PDF links worked, and the files downloaded without issues. The simplicity of the page (three buttons, three PDFs) made collection straightforward. The challenge is not access — it's that there simply isn't much documentation to collect.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
